1) Singing = “cursive for speech” (good intuition, here’s why it works)

Your analogy is actually solid:

Speech = printed text
Singing = cursive (continuous, patterned flow)

But the deeper reason singing sticks better is this:

Singing = multi-channel encoding

When you sing, you’re not just using language—you’re stacking:
	•	rhythm (timing)
	•	melody (pitch pattern)
	•	prosody (emotional tone)
	•	motor patterning (breath + vocal control)
	•	prediction loops (you expect what comes next)

So instead of:

one pathway (words)

You get:

a braided rope of memory

⸻

Why people remember songs but not text

Because songs create:

structured redundancy

	•	if you forget words → melody cues them
	•	if you forget melody → rhythm cues it
	•	if both fail → emotion/context cues it

That’s why:

music is a compression + retrieval system

⸻

Transferable insight (this is the gold)

You can apply this to anything:
	•	learning → add rhythm/pattern
	•	speaking → use cadence intentionally
	•	teaching → layer structure + repetition

Rule:

The more channels you encode across, the harder it is to forget.

